<HL>
   International:
   Kuwait Sells Stake
   In Mount Charlotte
   To Brierley Firm
   ----
   By Richard L. Hudson and Richard E. Rustin
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<CO>
   U.MTC A.BRY MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
LODGING, HOTELS, MOTELS, LODGES, CAMPGROUNDS (LOD)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- The exiled Kuwaiti government, in its first
confirmed sale of shares since the Iraqi invasion, sold a
stake valued at about #60 million ($110.8 million) in British
hotel chain Mount Charlotte Investments PLC to a company
controlled by New Zealand's Sir Ron Brierley.
   The Kuwaiti transaction raised Sir Ron's stake in
Britain's second-biggest hotel operator to 39.9% from 29.8%,
triggering a London Stock Exchange rule requiring that an
investor launch a public tender offer after his stake passes
30%. The New Zealand industrialist promptly launched a #386.6
million bid for the remaining 60.1% of Mount Charlotte shares
outstanding.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mount Charlotte's board rejected the Brierley bid.
   The sale by the Kuwait Investment Office, the main manager
of the Kuwaiti government-in-exile's $100 billion investment
portfolio, isn't part of a campaign to raise cash, a KIO
spokeswoman said. In the past decade, London-based KIO has
become known as a frequent buyer and seller of stocks. The
Mount Charlotte sale "is in line with our everyday investment
policy and doesn't spark off a spate of (KIO) selling," the
KIO spokeswoman said.
   Since Iraq's Aug. 2 invasion of Kuwait, London stock
traders have had occasional jitters at the thought that the
Kuwaitis might have to raise cash quickly. But at a news
conference here Friday, Sheik Ali Khalifa al-Sabah, the
Kuwaiti finance minister, indicated his government won't be
selling gold or stocks.
   Instead, he said the $5 billion that the Kuwaitis have
pledged for 1990 alone to support the West's Persian Gulf
operations will come from "liquid assets," cash reserves and
sales of short-term market instruments "in various
currencies." He said about half the money has been raised.
   But he indicated that financial pressures on the Kuwaitis
will continue. Kuwait has a bill of $50 million to $100
million a month for support of its exiled citizens. And
military and economic aid to the West and moderate Arab
nations will continue over the next year or two, he added.
   "I'm not worried about 1990. I worry more about 1991 and
1992," Sheik Ali said. He added that Kuwait is prepared to
contribute to such future aid, but would prefer to see it
done through the International Monetary Fund or other world
bodies, and without the normal obligations that the IMF
requires of a receiving country.
   The KIO declined to discuss details of the Mount Charlotte
sale. But Stuart Mitchell, managing director of a London
subsidiary of Brierley Investments Ltd., said a KIO broker,
Hoare Govett Ltd., initiated the sale talks. The per-share
price for the 88.8 million-share parcel, a 10.1% stake, was
"marginally less" than 73 pence, Mr. Mitchell said. The
Brierley Investments bid for the remaining 60.1% of Mount
Charlotte that it doesn't already own is 73 pence a share.
   Mount Charlotte climbed 11 pence to 70 1/2 pence
yesterday.
   London financial analysts speculated that the Brierley bid
was a formality forced by the stock exchange bid rules,
rather than a serious attempt to buy 100% of the company.
When asked about that speculation, Mr. Mitchell said: "Quite
simply, we made the offer because we are required to under
the City code. We'll be quite relaxed about any level of
acceptance that we get." The City of London is the London
financial community.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900925-0128
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900925-0128.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Ford Reduces
   Cash Rebates
   On Some Cars
   ---
   Effort to Shore Up Profits
   Will Mean Higher Prices
   On High-Volume Lines
   ----
   By Gregory A. Patterson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   F
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   DETROIT -- Ford Motor Co., trying to shore up profits amid
an industrywide sales decline, is raising prices on some of
its highest volume cars by reducing the cash rebates to
consumers.
   Ford cut the rebate on its 1991 Taurus, Sable,
Thunderbird, Cougar, Tempo and Topaz models to $500 from the
previous $750. The rebate on the Ford Crown Victoria was cut
to $500 from $1,000.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The auto maker also totally eliminated the rebates to
consumers for the purchase of any of its 1990 models.
Instead, Ford said it will offer incentives on those cars to
dealers. Dealers may then use the money to cut the price to
showroom shoppers, boost local advertising or simply to
sweeten their own profits on the vehicles.
   The rebate changes take effect Thursday and are set to run
through Dec. 11.
   The Ford action appears to be a bold, and perhaps risky,
move to staunch the continuing rise in buyer-incentive
outlays, which have hit record levels this year. In the
second quarter, for example, Ford spent an average $1,050 per
vehicle on buyer incentives, compared with only about $600 a
vehicle a year earlier.
   But Ford's move is risky because its two largest
competitors, General Motors Corp. and Toyota Motor Co., have
been particularly aggressive in using incentives recently. GM
is the only Big Three auto maker to avoid a drop in
car-market share this year, and Toyota has a record 8.8%
market share in the first eight months of 1990. Should Ford
wind up losing market share this year, it will be the
company's first such decline since 1986.
   But Ford appears to be more worried by the plunge in its
earnings than by the erosion in its U.S. market share. Partly
because of incentive outlays, Ford's second quarter net
income plunged 45% to $770.7 million, or $1.67 a share. Some
analysts say Ford may post a loss for its U.S. auto
operations in the third quarter, although the company
wouldn't comment on that yesterday.
   A spokesman for GM, traditionally the industry's pricing
leader, said the auto maker will study Ford's pricing move
before it responds, if at all.
   The conflicting desires to boost market share and earnings
have caused Ford to waffle on pricing strategy in recent
months. In July, Ford initially said it would boost base
prices by 4% to 5% on most of its 1991 models. But seven
weeks later the auto maker scaled back many of those
increases to less than 3%.
   Analysts said Ford also could change its mind about its
latest pricing move. The new program "sounds like an
experiment to see what would happen to sales if incentives
weren't as generous," surmised Ronald Glantz, an analyst with
Dean Witter Reynolds in San Francisco. "It's an experiment
that can be quickly ended if sales decline," he added.
   Ford characterized yesterday's move as a step away from
incentives. "We've been saying all along that we would like
to get out of the incentive business, but that just hasn't
happened," a Ford spokesman said. "This could be construed as
a step in that direction."
   Ford's dealers, who criticized direct consumer incentives
as being too complicated, applauded the new program. Dealers
said yesterday's move will simplify the cash-back incentive
programs on the 1991 models, and give dealers a stronger
marketing role in clearing out the 1990s.
   "It's basically an answer to the dealers," said Craig
Kapson, general sales manager of Jordan Ford in Mishawaka,
Ind. "They've made it so that the dealer can negotiate with
the customer."
   The new incentive plan, like the old one, offers discount
finance rates as an alternative to rebates. It's also similar
to the old program in another respect: It doesn't offer any
consumer incentives on Ford's most profitable vehicles. Those
are the Ford Explorer, a four-door Jeep-like vehicle, and the
Lincoln luxury cars. Sales of those vehicles have been
strong.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900925-0127
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900925-0127.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Diamandis, Two Top Aides Quit
   Hachette in a Rift Over Magazines
   ----
   By Patrick M. Reilly
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7
</SO>
<CO>
   F.HAC WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Founder Peter Diamandis and two other top
executives of Hachette S.A.'s Diamandis Communications Inc.
abruptly left the magazine publisher in a falling out with
their French parent company.
   Hachette said in a statement yesterday that it would
rename the unit Hachette Magazines. Hachette said that while
Mr. Diamandis's contract does not expire until Dec. 31, it
had been "mutually agreed that his employment would
terminate" yesterday.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Diamandis, who was until yesterday president and chief
executive officer of Diamandis Communications Inc., declined
to comment. The 58-year-old executive had said recently that
he wanted to stay with DCI, the magazine company he had
created in October 1987, when he led a leveraged buy-out of
CBS Inc.'s magazine division. Six months after the buy-out,
Mr. Diamandis sold his company for $712 million to Hachette,
making a substantial profit.
   But in recent months, Hachette and Mr. Diamandis clashed
openly over the handling of DCI magazines; Mr. Diamandis said
he felt a personal allegiance to the editors and publishers
of his magazines. Mr. Diamandis and Hachette failed to come
to terms at a board meeting last Tuesday, where Mr. Diamandis
reportedly opposed a planned restructuring that would involve
layoffs and the possible sale of magazine titles.
   Hachette executives didn't return calls, but in a release,
Daniel Filipacchi, vice chairman of Hachette, said the
company was committed to the magazines "while striving to
maximize the company's efficiency and reducing waste." Mr.
Filipacchi will take on Mr. Diamandis's role as chairman and
chief executive of Hachette magazines.
   Also departing yesterday were two other high-ranking
executives who with Mr. Diamandis had formed the management
group that led the buy-out of CBS. They include Robert F.
Spillane, executive vice president of DCI, and Arthur Sukel,
senior vice president and chief financial officer. By
yesterday afternoon, the offices of Messrs. Diamandis,
Spillane and Sukel had been cleaned out and personal items
stored in boxes, according to company insiders. Messrs.
Spillane and Sukel also couldn't be reached.
   DCI publishes 17 magazines and about 50 special, one-time
titles, and has annual revenue of about $600 million.
   Trouble between Hachette and Mr. Diamandis began last
spring, when Hachette forced Mr. Diamandis to put Woman's Day
-- one of the largest-circulation magazines in the U.S. -- on
the auction block. Mr. Diamandis at first strongly opposed
the move, then finally agreed to it. By late July, Woman's
Day had not been sold, and Hachette had been forced to knock
down its price to under $175 million from more than $200
million. But possible buyers reportedly still think the price
is too high, and no sale has materialized.
   Mr. Diamandis was also angered by Hachette's decision
earlier this month to close down Memories magazine, a
news-nostalgia magazine that he had helped create.
   Late yesterday, Hachette moved quickly to take tighter
control of the company. Besides Mr. Filipacchi, who will take
personal control of the magazines unit, all editors will
report to Jean-Louis Ginibre, Hachette senior vice president
and editorial director. David J. Pecker, formerly vice
president and controller of DCI, was named chief operating
officer and chief financial officer of Hachette Magazines.
   The abrupt departure of Mr. Diamandis now raises the
question of how Hachette will treat other top managers,
editors, and publishers at the company, many whom have close
professional and personal allegiances to Mr. Diamandis.
   Mr. Diamandis won many friends by spreading the wealth to
employees through stock options and bonuses. At the time of
the leveraged buy-out, top executives were issued stock
options in DCI, which Mr. Diamandis intended to take public.
When Hachette purchased DCI, it purchased the options of the
executives. Mr. Diamandis made sure that lower rungs of
employees, even secretaries, received stock or at least
one-time payments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900925-0126
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900925-0126.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   IMF to Assist
   Countries Hurt
   By Gulf Crisis
   ---
   Panel Agrees to Lend More
   To Nations That Adopt
   Sound Economic Plans
   ----
   By Peter Truell
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A24
</SO>
<CO>
   FORGN MDEST EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
PETROLEUM (PET)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The International Monetary Fund's
policy-making panel agreed the agency should promptly lend
more to countries hurt by the Persian Gulf crisis, provided
they are adopting sound economic adjustment policies of their
own.
   But the panel, the so-called interim committee, said the
increased lending can be done through existing lending
mechanisms, and it didn't recommend any specific new fund for
lending to countries hard-pressed by higher oil prices.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Canadian Finance Minister Michael Wilson, who heads the
interim committee, said the panel's agreement "provides a
framework" for the IMF to provide help "on an expedited
basis."
   IMF managing director Michel Camdessus said that the
increased lending would be evident by early next year. But he
added, "We won't put money down the drain. Help will go to
countries with good adjustment policies."
   Messrs. Wilson and Camdessus spoke at a joint news
conference yesterday after the release of the Interim
Committee's statement, which sets out IMF policy for the
coming months. President Bush is scheduled to address the
opening session of the annual meetings of the full IMF and
World Bank here today.
   The interim committee, which normally convenes prior to
the IMF and World Bank's annual and semiannual meetings,
warned that the recent rise in oil prices "may contribute to
cost-price pressures and moderate growth, particularly in oil
importing countries." It cautioned against attempts to
cushion consumers through subsidies, price controls or higher
wages, and advised that oil prices should be passed on
quickly to consumers.
   The interim committee indicated that the IMF will use
several existing lending mechanisms to help countries damaged
by higher energy costs. It will employ its Enhanced
Structural Adjustment Facility, from which it lends to the
very poorest countries at subsidized interest rates. It also
will increase standby loans and use of its so-called
compensatory and contingency financing facility.
   The IMF committee hasn't given estimates of the additional
lending it will do, but Mr. Camdessus said he expects the
organization's existing resources to be "adequate" at least
until March 1993, assuming the $65 billion capital increase
recently approved by the organization's members is completed
soon.
   While it praised Saudi Arabia, Japan, the European
Community and Japan for pledging to help severely affected
Mideast countries, the IMF's policy-making body still is
looking to some of the Fund's richer members for further
help. It said that it hoped "all members that are in a
position to do so will collaborate" in this assistance. Last
week, the IMF's managing director discussed the likelihood
that the agency might act as an intermediary between oil-rich
countries and those suffering balance-of-payments
difficulties.
   Treasury Undersecretary for International Affairs David
Mulford is scheduled to head an international meeting
Wednesday to discuss how to coordinate international plans to
lend between $13 billion and $16 billion to Egypt, Turkey and
probably Jordan, three countries most severely affected by
the Persian Gulf crisis.
   The IMF already is producing preliminary estimates of the
damage to the "front-line states." In an internal memorandum,
Jacques de Groote, the IMF's director for Turkey and several
other countries, said the crisis "will cause an annual loss
to Turkey of about $5 billion."
   Mr. de Groote's memo lists measures Turkey has taken since
the crisis. These include big rises in prices for gas and
diesel; higher sales and import taxes; sales of public land
and other revenue-raising efforts. Because of this prompt
action, and with "appropriate" foreign financing, Turkey
"will be able to restore a viable balance of payments
position, reduce inflation, and maintain relatively high real
income growth," Mr. de Groote concludes.
   Despite what Mr. Camdessus called the "mini-oil crisis"
that has followed Iraq's Aug. 2 invasion of Kuwait, the
interim committee -- tracking the statement released Saturday
by the seven major industrialized nations -- said economic
growth is still continuing "albeit at a slower pace."
   It also delivered a strong message calling for completion
of the current round of international trade talks being held
under the world trade treaty, the General Agreement on
Tarriffs and Trade. It said a new accord would strengthen the
world economy and ensure the success of reforms in eastern
Europe and in developing nations.
   Mr. Bush is expected to focus his remarks today on arguing
that there is an urgent need for more progress in the GATT
talks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
