<HL>
   Stamford Capital
   Dissolves Boutique
   Of Lehman Alumni
   ----
   By Michael Siconolfi
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<CO>
   PA WNEWS AXP
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES (SCR)
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- A fledgling investment boutique of Lehman
Brothers alumni folded, and several top partners joined
another Wall Street firm headed by former Lehman executives.
   The dissolution of Stamford Co. stemmed from a sudden
pullback of capital by its parent, Stamford Capital Group
Inc., amid the deep slump in the investment banking business.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Launched last year by Sheldon S. Gordon, former vice
chairman at Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc., Stamford was
modeled after Wall Street's traditional investment banking
partnerships. But trading losses and a slowdown in merger
activity and other traditional investment banking activities
stung the firm badly.
   The demise of the firm -- its core partners were all
former executives of Lehman Brothers, which was bought by
Shearson in 1984 -- is a vivid reminder of the difficulty
facing Wall Street's investment banking boutiques these days.
   "The real lesson here is that it has to be the right idea
with the right people at the right time," Mr. Gordon said,
adding that he will concentrate now on private investing. "We
had the right idea with the right people, but the timing was
poor."
   Several of Stamford's top partners, meanwhile, have jumped
to another securities firm with strong Lehman ties: Primerica
Corp.'s Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. They include James
Boshart, who was hired at Lehman Brothers 20 years ago by
Lewis Glucksman, who now is a Smith Barney vice chairman. Mr.
Boshart will head Smith Barney's corporate finance
operations.
   Clifford Goldman, Stamford's former chief financial
officer and another former Lehman executive, will become a
managing director supervising Smith Barney's administration.
Mr. Goldman initially will focus on the financial reporting
of the firm's businesses, a Smith Barney spokesman said.
   Another senior Stamford partner, Judah Frankel, will join
Smith Barney as a managing director in its mortgage-backed
securities department. Several other former Lehman executives
have left Stamford in the past several months, as the firm's
fortunes have sagged.
   Meanwhile, some of Stamford's business lines are likely to
be bought soon by senior management as separate entities,
people familiar with the firm said. For example, Stamford's
corporate finance and mergers group, which focused on
companies involving transactions valued at between $15
million and $150 million, is likely to be bought out by a
small group led by Arnold Hoffman, another former Lehman
executive who ran Stamford's middle-market merger activity,
the people said.
   A planned partner in the new entity, to be called Middle
Market Group L.P., is Shearson Lehman Brothers itself.
Shearson's interest stemmed from a joint venture worked out
with Stamford last year, in which each firm received revenue
from certain transactions involving midsized companies.
   A spokesman for Shearson, a unit of American Express Co.,
said, "We'll continue to have an interest in the
middle-market group."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900925-0119
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900925-0119.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Anyone Who Can Sell Green Eggs
   And Ham Is Worth Listening To
   ----
   By L.A. Winokur
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   Add another familiar name to the list of management
mavens: Theodor S. Geisel.
   S as in Seuss. As in Dr. Seuss.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The children's author who put "Green Eggs and Ham" on
practically every kid's breakfast plate is being served up as
recommended fare to grown-up managers. Cynthia Eisenhauer,
for one, urges her staff at the Iowa Department of Employment
Services, where she is director, to savor the wisdom in the
86-year-old author's most recent book, "Oh, the Places You'll
Go]"
   Here is one such morsel:
   You have brains in your head.
   You have feet in your shoes.
   You can steer yourself
   any direction you choose.
   "It's inspirational and encourages people to set high
standards and work to achieve them without being
discouraged," exclaims Ms. Eisenhauer.
   Carolyn B. Elman, executive director of the American
Business Women's Association, agrees. She has been pushing
the book to her group's 100,000 members. Unlike many
how-to-succeed books, she contends, "this book lets you know
everyone fails at some time and that you have to pick
yourself up and just go on." Dr. Seuss's prescription:
   Out there things can happen
   and frequently do
   to people as brainy
   and footsy as you.
   And when things start to happen,
   don't worry. Don't stew.
   Just go right along.
   You'll start happening too.
   Nearly 800,000 copies of the book have been sold since it
was released early this year, reports Random House, which is
marketing it "as a book for anyone starting out on a new
adventure in life," says a spokeswoman. Described on its
jacket as a graduation speech for "out-starting upstarts of
all ages," the book has been on the New York Times fiction
best-seller list for more than 30 weeks.
   Like Grinches, some big-name management gurus are giving
their newest colleague the brushoff. "I haven't gotten to it
yet," says Peter Drucker, who suggests he prefers Shakespeare
to Seuss as a management tool.
   What does Dr. Seuss say about all this? "While I had no
intention of speaking directly to managers when I wrote the
book, I'm pleased when readers get something beyond what I
intended."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900925-0118
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900925-0118.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Dividend News:
   Corroon &amp; Black
   Holders to Receive
   Special Dividend
   ----
   By Beatrice E. Garcia
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9
</SO>
<CO>
   CBL AOC U.WIL
</CO>
<IN>
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
INSURANCE (INS)
FULL LINE INSURANCE (INF)
</IN>
<LP>
   Corroon &amp; Black Corp. declared a special cash dividend of
$2.50 a share as an enticement to shareholders, who will soon
be voting on the company's merger with London-based Willis
Faber PLC.
   Because Corroon will be filing supplemental proxy
materials with the Securities and Exchange Commission, the
New York-based insurance broker postponed the special
shareholders meeting for voting on the Willis Faber merger
from Friday until Oct. 4. The new proxy material, due to be
mailed to holders tomorrow, will provide details on the
special dividend and other recent events, including Aon
Corp.'s unsolicited $40-a-share, or $840 million, bid for
Corroon.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The insurance broker rejected Aon's offer last Tuesday.
Chicago-based Aon withdrew its bid last Friday.
   Robert Cuthbert, Corroon's chief financial officer, said
the special dividend was needed "to facilitate the
transaction." The special dividend would "focus everyone's
attention on the deal" as originally structured, he added.
   When the Willis Faber merger was announced in early June,
it was valued at $34.72 a share, or $712.3 million. Since
then, Willis Faber's share price has dropped, lowering the
deal's total value.
   Corroon's stock jumped several points when the Aon offer
was announced, but it fell back when it appeared that the
Corroon board still favored the Willis Faber merger and Aon
wouldn't pursue a hostile offer. Corroon shares rose 25 cents
to a $29.50 closing in New York Stock Exchange composite
trading yesterday.
   The Corroon board declared the special dividend at a board
meeting held Sunday. The special dividend is payable to
Corroon's holders of record on the effective date of the
proposed merger with Willis Faber. The special dividend won't
be paid unless the merger is completed. The special dividend
was also approved by the Willis Faber board.
   Willis Faber shareholders will be voting Friday on the
merger with Corroon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
