<HL>
   The Worker Count -- A Special Report
   ---
   Labor Letter:
   A Special News Report on People
   And Their Jobs in Offices,
   Fields and Factories
   ----
   By Albert R. Karr
</HL>
<DATE>
09/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
PETROLEUM (PET)
</IN>
<LP>
   THE 1990 CENSUS reflects restless feet in the nation's
labor force.
   Preliminary population figures, the first census reports
so far, show West Virginia with a 9% drop since 1980, the
largest for a state. As coal mechanization sped on, 143,000
people left the Mountain State by 1989, an earlier report
said. The employment slump ended recently, but "our big
concern now is what a national recession will do" to the
state's jobs, says Edward Merrifield, a state labor research
official.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Analysts warn that steady out-migration from an area can
cause a downward job spiral, deterring new business as the
labor supply dwindles. Industrial states like Michigan,
Illinois and Pennsylvania also lost people, the early 1990
figures suggest. But a combined 7.1 million people migrated
to sunny California, Arizona, Texas and Florida between 1980
and 1989, many taking new service jobs.
   The worker migration means "another union organizing task,
in a more hostile location," complains AFL-CIO economist John
Zalusky.
                                                                                                       

   UNIONS ESCALATE efforts to influence reapportionment in
wake of census.
   The American Federation of Federal, State, County and
Municipal Employees leads a drive to help Democrats control
16 key state legislatures and win hot gubernatorial contests
in California, Texas and Florida Nov. 6. The governors' veto
power will give them a "key role" when state lawmakers start
congressional redistricting in 1991, notes AFL-CIO political
chief John Perkins. "This is when your investment pays
dividends for five elections {through the year 2000}," a Food
Workers official adds.
   Some 45 unions, including auto, steel and communications
workers, teachers and letter carriers, contributed over half
of $5 million raised for the Democrats' five-year "Project
500," and unions "give us the bodies" for polling and
research, a party spokesman says.
                                                                                                       

   SEX, AGE AND SKILL factors loom large for the future work
force.
   The Bureau of Labor Statistics sees an increase of older
workers by 2000. Of men over 54 years old, 68% will be
working, up from 67% in 1988, and of women in the same age
group, 49% will be working, up from 43.5%. But with new
census data, the agency may boost those numbers even further,
showing more oldsters on the job, BLS statistician Howard
Fullerton says. By 2000, the median worker age will rise to
35, and 85% of new workers will be less technically trained
women and minorities, concludes a Purdue University study.
   The census reports will show a sizable widening of the pay
gap between high-school and college graduates, reflecting the
decisions of many to skip college in the 1980s, says
University of Maryland economist Frank Levy.
   That gap rose from a median $2,659 for men and $5,486 for
women, ages 25 to 34, to an inflation-adjusted $9,089 and
$7,812, respectively, from 1979 to 1987.
                                                                                                       

   STATES LOSING JOBS get some advice from Hudson Institute
official William Johnston: Don't try to lure new factories in
this service economy. Instead, "visit {Disney Chairman}
Michael Eisner to see if he wants to locate a theme park" in
the area.
                                                                                                       

   UNDERCOUNTING could fuel legislative moves to boost
immigration quotas by showing an excessive labor shortage,
says National Planning Association economist Richard Belous.
If short counts are concentrated in certain immigrant-heavy,
low-income localities, they could also reduce federal
job-training grants.
                                                                                                       

   DOWN ON THE FARM: They aren't keeping them there. About
3.7 million people were working on more-mechanized farms and
ranches in mid-July, down 3% from the same 1989 week and 19%
from 1980, the Agriculture Department said. But hired hands
are on the rise, supplanting many farm-family workers.
                                                                                                       

   POPULATION AGE CHANGES have a marked effect on
unemployment rates.
   So concludes a new study by Paul Flaim, BLS chief of labor
force statistics. An influx of post-World War II baby boomers
into the job market helped push the jobless rate upward in
the 1960s and 1970s. "Short on skills and work experience,
youths could not readily substitute for older workers," so
employers were less eager to hire them, Mr. Flaim says.
   But maturing and even "graying" of the boomers sparked the
1980s decline in the rate. So did a drop in the number of
teenagers, along with a shrinkage in the size of the work
force. Changing age demographics, not any rise in the demand
for labor, explain a 10-year drop in the jobless rate from
5.9% to 5.3% by 1989, Mr. Flaim argues.
   In the '90s, a further shrinkage of young job seekers is
expected, but many employers will stiffen demands to show
skills.
                                                                                                       

   THE CHECKOFF: Noting that no labor-market data will emerge
from the 1990 census until 1992 or later, economist Sar
Levitan muses, "The more advanced the technology, the slower
the data publication." . . . No solace here: For those who
wonder about domestic energy capacity with Iraqi-held oil
shut off, the Census Bureau says oil and gas extraction
employment is down 25% from 1980.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900925-0096
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900925-0096.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Law:
   Judge Orders Milken Sentencing Memo
   Released by U.S., With Some Deletions
   ----
   By Laurie P. Cohen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
SECURITIES (SCR)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- A federal judge ordered the government to
release to the news media today an edited version of its
sentencing memorandum concerning Michael Milken, who is
scheduled to be sentenced next Monday.
   The memorandum, filed in court under seal this month,
contains information about the six securities fraud-related
crimes to which Mr. Milken pleaded guilty in April and a host
of other alleged crimes that the government believes he
committed. The memo, designed to encourage federal Judge
Kimba Wood to impose a stiff sentence on the former Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. junk-bond chief, is more than 200 pages
long.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In her order making the memorandum public, Judge Wood
ordered the government to delete names of unindicted
co-conspirators and of other individuals and entities who
remain under investigation. Judge Wood also ordered
prosecutors to delete the portions of the memo that relate to
Mr. Milken's brother, Lowell Milken.
   Lowell Milken was charged with securities and tax fraud in
an indictment filed last year, but the government agreed to
dismiss all charges against Lowell Milken when his brother
agreed to plead guilty.
   Meanwhile, Michael Milken's lawyers said they would
release their client's own memorandum, which seeks to rebut
many of the government's charges, today. Mr. Milken's
attorneys had sought to bar the release of either of the
memos until the sentencing.
   Lawyers for Mr. Milken argued that early release of the
memos could lead to "improper pressure" on the court. But
Judge Wood said that "delaying release may well prejudice the
ability of the press to understand the substance" of the
government's allegations. She added, "I'm not going to be
influenced by any publicity."
   It appears that the government's memorandum contains much
information that has never been made public. Yesterday
afternoon, lawyers for three "John Does" filed sealed memos
with the court asking that the government refrain from
releasing portions of the government's sentencing memo that
refer to their clients. The identities of the three clients
isn't known, and none of the three law firms has ever
appeared before on documents filed in connection with the
case against Mr. Milken.
   Still unresolved yesterday was whether Judge Wood, in
handing down a sentence, would even consider the allegations
of wrongdoing beyond the crimes to which Mr. Milken pleaded
guilty. If she agrees to the government's request that she
consider the further allegations, Mr. Milken would be
entitled to a hearing in which he could seek to defend
himself. Regardless of whether additional allegations are
considered, the maximum sentence for his crimes is 28 years
in prison. But the sentencing judge has wide discretion
within that limitation.
   One of the six counts to which Mr. Milken pleaded guilty
involves a conspiracy he engaged in with convicted former
stock speculator Ivan Boesky to violate the law. Judge Wood
said that neither the government's nor Mr. Milken's
sentencing memos provided enough information to determine the
extent of the conspiracy without a hearing.
   Arthur Liman, an attorney for Mr. Milken, said he would
submit additional details of Mr. Milken's illegal activities
involving Mr. Boesky by tomorrow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900925-0095
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900925-0095.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Newmont Australia
   Gets Support in Bid
   For BHP Gold Mines
</HL>
<DATE>
09/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16
</SO>
<CO>
   A.NEW NEM A.BHG BHP
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
</IN>
<LP>
   DENVER -- Newmont Mining Corp. said it agreed to support a
proposal by its 24%-owned Newmont Australia Ltd. to acquire
BHP Gold Mines Ltd. in a stock swap valued at about 475
million Australian dollars (US$394 million).
   Newmont Mining rejected an earlier offer by Poseidon Gold
Ltd., an Australian concern, to acquire the Newmont Australia
shares it doesn't own in a stock swap valued at A$780
million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Newmont Australia said its directors and the directors of
BHP agreed to the new proposal and recommended the stock deal
to BHP shareholders.
   Broken Hill Proprietary, an Australian steel, mining and
oil company, holds about 55% of BHP and would hold about 23%
of the merged company if the offer is accepted. Newmont
Mining would hold about 14% of the new company, which would
be renamed, according to Newmont Mining Vice Chairman Richard
Leather.
   "The combined company will be a stronger and more
attractive company with a stronger operating group, stronger
management and stronger prospects," said Mr. Leather.
Acquiring BHP would boost Newmont Australia's 1991 gold
production some 75% to 790,000 ounces from 450,000 ounces, he
said. Combined, the company would have around four million
ounces of gold reserves at its gold mines and another 11
million ounces of resources that it might mine in the future.
BHP and Newmont Australia jointly own the Telfer Gold Mine,
which is expected to produce about 300,000 ounces of gold in
1990.
   In August, Newmont Mining sold nearly half of its shares,
or 20% of the stock outstanding, of Newmont Australia to
Poseidon Gold for A$166 million. At that time, Poseidon
offered to acquire the rest of Newmont Australia stock by
swapping one share of Poseidon stock for every two shares of
Newmont Australia stock. Since then, both Newmont Australia
and Newmont Mining have rejected that offer.
   Newmont Mining said it will continue to explore proposals
to liquidate its holdings in Newmont Australia after the BHP
deal is completed. Newmont Mining has said it is interested
in pursuing other gold prospects in Indonesia and Papua New
Guinea instead of retaining its interest in Australian gold
production.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
