</DOCID>
<HL>
   Oil Prices Hit
   Highest Levels
   In a Decade
   ---
   Some Crudes Soar $3 a Barrel
   In Wake of Iraq's Threat
   Against Mideast Fields
   ----
   By James Tanner
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   Panic buying in the wake of Iraqi threats against Middle
East oil fields drove petroleum prices to the highest levels
in a decade.
   The run-up of more than $3 a barrel for some crudes added
to the prospect of inflation, depressed the U.S. stock market
and increased support for tapping into the U.S. Strategic
Petroleum Reserve.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Only a month after breaking the $30 a barrel mark, several
crudes surged beyond $39 a barrel in trading with the U.S.
futures price reaching $39.20 briefly. Some North Sea oil was
valued at $40 a barrel on European spot markets in late
trading, although details of transactions at those levels
weren't confirmed.
   Even though it dropped back from the high, crude traded on
the New York Mercantile Exchange posted a futures record.
Crude oil for November delivery was up $2.82 a barrel to
settle at $38.25. That was the highest price for this type of
oil, a light low-sulfur crude, since West Texas Intermediate,
the U.S. benchmark, reached $39.80 a barrel in the cash
market in March 1980.
   Fuels reflected the escalation in crude oil prices. In
U.S. futures trading, heating oil and unleaded gasoline for
October delivery rose nearly seven cents a gallon each to
settle at $1.04 a gallon each.
   The oil-price surge followed a weekend statement from
Baghdad by Saddam Hussein that he would strike at Middle East
oil fields before he would let U.S.-led sanctions "strangle"
Iraq. Although the Iraqi president has issued warnings
against a U.S. attack on Iraq, his new remarks were
interpreted as indicating he might strike first.
   Iraq failed in its eight-year war with Iran to halt that
nation's oil flow. Oil and military analysts questioned
whether Iraq could be any more successful in destroying Saudi
Arabia's well-defended installations if it tried.
   Still, Saddam Hussein's statement advanced war fears
another notch and kept alive the possibility of major
disruptions of the flow of oil from the Middle East, which
holds the bulk of the world's reserves. As a result, the new
threats were quickly reflected in higher petroleum prices
around the world as trading opened yesterday.
   "The market is very, very jittery," said Peter Beutel,
director of the energy group at Pegasus Econometric. "People
are afraid we are going to see a war in the Middle East."
   Few oil analysts were bold enough to forecast the
direction of the oil market after the rapid escalation of
recent days. Several suggested that $40 is no longer out of
reach and that $65 may well be the likely target, as some
studies have predicted, if war breaks out.
   Most private and government energy officials continued to
maintain that the industry's supply-demand fundamentals don't
justify the current levels of pricing. Barring an extremely
cold winter or a disruption, oil supplies should be ample,
they said.
   "The market is anticipating an awful lot," said Peter
Gignoux, manager of the international energy desk in London
for Shearson Lehman Brothers. "Without hostilities, we are
totally, fully priced."
   Most oil economists agreed that oil market participants
are clearly reacting to the words of Saddam Hussein. "The
market now is suggesting we are on a war footing," said
Lawrence Goldstein, president of the Petroleum Industry
Research Foundation, "and a war premium has been built into
the {pricing} system."
   The Petroleum Industry Research Foundation, a non-profit
organization that receives some financing from oil companies,
is a leading supporter of opening up the U.S. Strategic
Petroleum Reserve to help damp the escalation in oil prices.
Its position is that the artificially high prices damage
economies.
   "We believe it's time to release SPR barrels" to prevent
further deterioration of the U.S. economy, said Mr.
Goldstein.
   Under the law that established the reserve, President Bush
must make a "finding" that there is justification for
commercial releases of oil from the reserve because of an oil
shortage. But proponents of opening the reserve contend that
the evidence of supply restraints won't show up until long
after the shortage has begun.
   A test of the system is planned for next month, however.
Recent legislation approved by Congress to establish a new
target of one billion barrels of oil for the reserve, which
contains slightly under 600 million barrels, would permit
withdrawals, totaling as much as five million barrels, in
such a test.
   "It could have the same psychological effect on the market
that a commercial release would have," Mr. Goldstein said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900925-0080
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900925-0080.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing:
   BankAmerica and Barclays
   To Link Traveler's Checks
   ----
   By Stephen Kreider Yoder
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   BAC BCS AXP
</CO>
<IN>
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BANKS (BNK)
MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)
</IN>
<LP>
   BankAmerica Corp. will join forces with London's Barclays
PLC in an assault on American Express Co.'s grip on the
lucrative traveler's check business.
   The two companies hope the merger will capitalize on
banks' reluctance to sell checks bearing the name of a
competing bank or financial institution -- such as American
Express. And the new operation's combined size could give it
a boost. "It's our intent to challenge for leadership in the
traveler's check business," said Gordon DeLang, senior vice
president of BankAmerica's BA Checque Corp.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But American Express, although its share has slipped, has
long been the dominant player in the market, and many
analysts doubt that the new combination will have much effect
on it. Estimates of American Express's share of the
world-wide market range from 39% to close to 50%. In
addition, American Express checks carry a cachet with
consumers that other companies haven't been able to match.
   American Express issued $24.1 billion in traveler's checks
last year. Mr. DeLang wouldn't disclose BankAmerica's or
Barclay's check sales, but said he expected the Interpayment
venture to do more than $12 billion in sales in 1991.
   BankAmerica, based in San Francisco, said it agreed to
acquire an equity position in Barclays's Interpayment
Services Ltd. unit and to fold its traveler's check
operations into the company, which will then issue both
banks' traveler's checks. Moreover, Interpayment Services
will provide clearing services for other banks who decide to
issue traveler's checks under their own names. The venture
also will issue checks under the brands of BankAmerica, Visa
and MasterCard.
   The deal also could benefit from banks' concerns about
selling American Express checks when they sell Visa or
MasterCard credit cards, said Spencer Nilson, publisher of
Nilson Report, a newsletter on the credit and traveler's
check industry. "The banks don't want (to work with) a
competitor to their credit cards," he said.
   The venture, said Mr. Nilson and other analysts, is a sign
of the times for the traveler's check industry, where profits
are being squeezed as consumers begin to use automated teller
machines as substitutes. World-wide traveler's check sales
will increase about 7% percent this year, to $58.5 billion,
Mr. Nilson said.
   "The business is still profitable but less profitable and
it's growing slower," said Mr. Nilson. "There's going to have
to be more consolidation -- more of this kind of thing."
   By joining forces with Barclays, BankAmerica taps into
Barclays strength in markets such as the U.K. and Canada.
While Bank of America issues only U.S. dollar checks,
Interpayment issues checks in the currencies of countries
such as Great Britain, Germany and France and has reciprocal
agreements with issuers of checks in Australian, New Zealand
and Italian currencies.
   Barclays, the world's largest issuer of Visa checks, will
benefit from BankAmerica's strength in Europe and Asia and
will gain access to BankAmerica's service organization. The
Interpayment joint venture will move its headquarters to New
York from London, Mr. DeLang said. The banks expect to
complete the venture in the fourth quarter of 1990, pending
regulatory approval, he said.
   American Express executives expressed confidence yesterday
that the joint agreement between BankAmerica and Barclays
won't have a significant impact on its traveler's check
revenue.
   According to Michael Goldstein, a senior research analyst
with Sanford C. Bernstein &amp; Co. in New York, American Express
will earn about $120 million in pretax profits this year from
its traveler's check operations, about the same amount it did
in 1989.
   "This is a slow growth business, but as interest rates
rise, it becomes more interesting because of the float," said
Mr. Goldstein. The float -- the period during which the
checks remain uncashed and the issuer has use of the money --
accounts for much of the profits American Express earns from
traveler's checks. "The same thing happened in the early
1980s, when interest rates were high," said Mr. Goldstein.
   Mr. Goldstein noted that many of the opportunist companies
that leaped into the traveler's check industry have since
closed or merged their operations. "I don't think this newest
development is going to hurt American Express in any
measurable way," he said. "American Express has a strong
brand franchise with adequate distribution. It has weathered
challenges in the past, and will probably do so again now."
   Mr. Nilson, the newsletter editor, said consumers aren't
likely to shift check-buying habits because of such mergers.
"It isn't going to change the consumer's perception," he
said.
   ---
   Jeffrey A. Trachtenberg contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
