<HL>
   Senate Clears Bill
   Designed to Protect
   Retirement Plans
   ----
   By Albert R. Karr
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A24
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Senate overwhelmingly approved
legislation aimed at restoring protection of older workers'
retirement benefits.
   The Senate voted 94-1 for the measure, after leading
backers and former opponents worked out a compromise. That
agreement between Howard Metzenbaum of Ohio and David Pryor
of Arkansas, Democrats pushing the bill, and Republicans
Orrin Hatch of Utah and John Heinz of Pennsylvania attempted
to meet employers' concerns that earlier versions would lead
to costly benefit packages and make it difficult for the
employers to offer early retirement to older employees.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Senior Bush administration officials had recommended that
the president veto an earlier version, but a White House
spokeswoman yesterday said that the administration hadn't
reviewed the compromise and didn't yet have a position on it.
The House hasn't yet moved ahead with its version of the
bill, and employers want to prevent the House from going
beyond the Senate compromise measure in assuring retiree
benefits.
   The Senate compromise measure would bar employers from
discriminating against older workers in providing such
benefits as pensions and disability payments. It eliminates a
provision that would have penalized employers retroactively,
for benefit plans that don't comply with the bill but would
have been in effect before its enactment.
   The agreement also allows employers to avoid
discrimination against older workers by combining benefits,
rather than considering each benefit separately. Non-union
employers would be given 180 days, instead of 60 days, to
comply with the new requirements.
   The legislation is designed to overturn a 1989 Supreme
Court ruling that gave employers wide leeway to restrict
retirement pension and health benefits. The ruling reversed
an appeals court decision that had favored June Betts, who
had to retire at age 61 because of illness after six years as
an Ohio speech pathologist. Because she was over 59, the
state denied disability in accordance with state law.
   The high court decision was one of several rulings that
civil-rights groups said rolled back much of the gains they
had made over the years in winning legal protection for
workers' rights.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900925-0057
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900925-0057.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Chase Manhattan,
   Two Top Executives
   Are Sued by a Holder
</HL>
<DATE>
09/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   CMB
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- A shareholder filed a lawsuit against Chase
Manhattan Corp. and its two top executives, accusing them of
making false and misleading statements about the bank's
financial condition in recent months.
   The lawsuit, filed in federal court in Manhattan, seeks to
be made a class action for all investors who bought Chase
stock between Jan. 17 and Friday, when Chase cut its dividend
50% to 30 cents a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A Chase spokesman said the suit is without merit.
   The lawsuit alleges that the company's stock price was
artificially inflated in recent months because of misleading,
optimistic statements by Chase -- starting with the
announcement of a dividend increase Jan. 17.
   It also claims that Chase knew for several months that its
loan-loss reserves were inadequate and that it couldn't
afford to maintain its common-stock dividend. The lawsuit
alleges that Chase intentionally misled investors by
misrepresenting and not disclosing certain information about
the company's loan portfolio.
   "The numerous representations made by defendants
concerning Chase's improved financial condition, the adequacy
of the bank's loan-loss reserves and the projections for
accelerated earnings were materially false and misleading and
not reasonably based," the lawsuit said. "The increase in the
dividend in January 1990 was intended to mislead investors as
to the company's true financial condition."
   Chase, in addition to halving its dividend, announced
Friday that it was setting aside $650 million in the current
quarter as additional reserves against potential losses on
domestic loans, mainly in real estate. The company also is
reducing its 41,000-person staff by 5,000.
   In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange
yesterday, Chase closed at $11.125 a share, down $1.625. The
stock was trading at about $32 a share in mid-January, the
start of the period in question in the suit.
   Besides the company, the suit names Willard Butcher,
chairman and chief executive officer, and Thomas Labrecque,
president and chief operating officer. Mr. Butcher will
retire next month, and Mr. Labrecque will succeed him.
   The lawsuit, filed by Israel Margolies of Peoria, Ill.,
seeks unspecified damages. At least three other lawsuits
making the same claims also were filed in federal court
yesterday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
