<HL>
   Business Brief -- Emerson Electric Co.:
   Board Votes to Spin Off
   Firm's Defense Operations
</HL>
<DATE>
09/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<CO>
   EMR
</CO>
<IN>
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
ELECTRICAL COMPONENTS AND EQUIPMENT (ELQ)
</IN>
<LP>
   Emerson Electric Co., St. Louis, said its board approved a
plan to spin off its defense operations as a company to be
known as Esco Electronics Corp.
   Under the planned distribution, Emerson holders of record
as of Oct. 5 will receive one Esco share for each 20 shares
of Emerson. The company said the Securities and Exchange
Commission cleared the spinoff. The Esco shares will be
treated as a taxable distribution, it said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sales for the latest fiscal year of the units that will
comprise Esco totaled about $600 million, or 8% of Emerson's
overall sales. Pretax earnings were about $15 million, or
1.5% of the parent's overall pre-tax profit, Emerson said.
   Emerson also said it won't be suspended from competing for
U.S. government contracts. In May, Emerson pleaded guilty in
federal court in St. Louis to inflating cost proposals on
certain military contracts, agreeing to pay $14 million.
Since the settlement, the company's status as a potential
bidder had been under review.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900925-0023
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900925-0023.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International Brief -- Jose Maria Aristrain S.A.:
   Steelmaker Won't Sell Stake
   To Banesto and British Steel
</HL>
<DATE>
09/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   BST E.BCE EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)
</IN>
<LP>
   Jose Maria Aristrain S.A., a family-owned Spanish
steelmaker, canceled an agreement to sell 80% of its shares
to Banco Espanol de Credito's industrial holding company and
to British Steel PLC for about 40 billion pesetas ($407
million).
   Acquisition of the Aristrain stake would have converted
the holding company of Banco Espanol, which is known as
Banesto, into one of Spain's leading nongovernment-owned
steel companies. It also would have given British Steel an
important foothold in the Spanish market.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A Banesto official said the company will seek ways of
collaborating with British Steel.
   Aristrain officials weren't immediately available for
comment, and British Steel declined to make a statement.
   Under the accord, reached in July after months of
conflicting reports about the sale, Industrial &amp; Financiera
de Banesto S.A. -- 76%-owned by Banesto -- and British Steel
were each to have acquired 40% of Aristrain. The Aristrain
family was to have retained a 20% stake, half of which was to
be sold eventually to Spanish state-owned steelmaker Empresa
Nacional de Siderurgica S.A., or Ensidesa.
</TEXT>
