<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
09/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   STOCKS AND BONDS PLUNGED as oil prices soared to their
highest levels in a decade in reaction to hostile Iraqi
remarks. The Dow Jones industrials fell 59.41 points to
2452.97, their lowest point in 14 months. The 30-year
Treasury bond lost more than half a point, boosting its yield
to 9.17%, its highest since March 1989. Some crude prices
rose more than $3 a barrel, with several briefly surpassing
$40. Gold futures posted their sharpest one-day gain in three
years. London stocks sank to 20-month lows.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   MCA is talking with Matsushita about a possible
acquisition of the U.S. entertainment company by the Japanese
electronics giant for between $6.7 billion and $7.5 billion.
   ---
   Thousands of federal workers will be furloughed starting
next week under Bush administration plans unless a
last-minute budget pact is reached.
   ---
   The Fed's steady credit stance is reducing any chance of
avoiding a recession and could prolong one if it occurs,
according to some economists.
   ---
   Ford cut rebates to buyers of some of its most popular
cars. The move could be risky in light of aggressive use of
incentives by Toyota and GM.
                                                                                                       

   Toyota is running short of cars to sell, which is expected
to limit the company's gain in U.S. market share.
   ---
   The IMF should lend more money soon to nations hurt by the
Gulf crisis, provided they adopt sound economic policies, an
IMF panel concluded.
   ---
   Canada agreed to join the U.S. and Mexico in talks on a
free-trade pact. Separately, U.S. trade envoy Hills warned
that global trade negotiations could collapse over farm
subsidies.
   ---
   UAL's pilot leaders raised the possibility that the
unions' buy-out effort might fail, forcing a resumption of
conventional labor negotiations. The company's stock fell
$8.50 a share.
   ---
   Banking regulators would be forced to restrict risky
operations of weak banks and thrifts before they fail, under
a bill to be introduced by the Senate Banking panel chairman.
   ---
   An SEC plan to restrict money-market funds' purchases of
commercial paper that is below top grade faces opposition in
many quarters.
   ---
   Honda plans to make two air bags standard by late 1993 on
all its cars sold in the U.S. The move follows similar steps
by American auto makers.
   ---
   Hachette's Diamandis unit is losing its top three
officials, including founder Peter Diamandis, over
differences with the French parent firm.
   ---
   BankAmerica and Barclays are merging their traveler's
check operations in an assault on American Express, the
market's dominant player.
   ---
   Rodamco stunned holders of the Dutch investment fund by
suspending its policy of redeeming shares.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 162,210,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2452.97, off 59.41; transportation 841.90, off 34.76;
utilities 199.76, off 1.95.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3303.37,
off 12.63.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 131.54, off 0.21;
spot index 129.95, up 0.43.
   Dollar: 137.35 yen, up 0.70; 1.5590 marks, off 0.0195.
</TEXT>
